  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>The "about.com" bar is one way to do this.

When we send people out to remote bug trackers, we could wrap it in some
context. For example, We could ask them their email address, and if we can ask
them to tell us how it went a week later. We could do that by putting the remote
bug tracker in a frame, or by making an interstitial page that we take them to
before we take them to the real bug tracker page.

I like the about.com bar more, because it gives the person room to click around
and finally say, "I want to work on this," and then at *that* point we can ask
them for email address, etc.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg865">msg865 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: paulproteus</th>
   <th>Date: 2011-01-29.23:38:58</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>People keep asking this very reasonable question: "Has the OpenHatch website
connected anyone with a project?"

I seem to recall hearing a pleasant story that meant the answer was "Yes", but
we should do better at keeping track of this (and then we can use the
information about when we succeed to drive future changes to the site).

This is a bad "bug" in that it's hard to fix with a single git commit, but it
should start discussions about new features that could help us resolve this. (So
we can mark this as resolved once we have some sort of plan.)</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
